","1312":"1312","1453":"1453","1409":"1409","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Little Saxham, Suffolk, England":"Little Saxham, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hethe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Laurent, Normand, Philippe.","German: habitational name from Methau in Saxony.","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Mět</b> or <b>Měto</b> (see   Mieth  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mieth","meanings":["Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Mět</b>: either from a short form of the Old Sorbian personal name <i>Mětisław</i>, composed of the Old Slavic elements <i>met</i> ‘to throw’ (from <i>metati</i>) + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’ or ‘famous’ (from <i>slava</i> ‘glory’), or from a pet form of <i>Mertyn</i>, a Lower Sorbian form of   Martin  .","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>miet</i> ‘reward’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":3,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":16,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":25,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Hethe was born in 1312, in Little Saxham, Suffolk, England, his father, William Bruario Hethe, was 26 and his mother, Agnes, was 21. He had at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1312–":"1312–Surnud","1312–Male":"1312–Surnud","–1286":"–1286","–1327":"–1327","–Male":"Surnud","1335–1392":"1335–1392","1349–1409":"1349–1409","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud"